WHO   — ATARI 2600 · VCS — an exereunesis sphere — the teardown
WHAT  — The machine that made home gaming an industry ran on a cut-down 6502, a single clever video-and-sound chip, and just 128 bytes of RAM — with no framebuffer at all. Programmers had to 'race the beam', drawing each scanline in real time as the TV scanned it. Brutally hard, and the foundation of everything.
WHERE — the teardown — a made machine, opened and explored  Framework inputs: the chips; the buses; the spec; the lore  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)
WHY   — The machine that made home gaming an industry ran on a cut-down 6502, a single clever video-and-sound chip, and just 128 bytes of RAM — with no framebuffer at all. Programmers had to 'race the beam', drawing each scanline in real time as the TV scanned it. Brutally hard, and the foundation of everything.
